106. The Sequence of Tenses is nothing peculiar to Latin, but is familiar from English usage. Compare—

He fears that he may die. He feared that he might die.

The change from may to might, owing to the change in the main verb from seara to feared, corresponds to the change in Latin from

the present to the imperfect subjunctive. The above in Latin

would be - Timet ne moriatur.

Timebat ne moreretur.

The laws of Tense·Sequence do not apply with equal stringency to all dependent constructions and were often disregarded.
